title: For Sale:  FAT 42 Carcano 91/41
postcontent: I have for sale from my collection a 6.5 Carcano 91/41. Built by Terni(FAT) in 1942, the 91/41 improves upon the M91 with two sets of sling attachment points and a rear sight that graduates from 300 to 1000 meters. Stock has no cracks or serious damage and features a Terni cartouche. Stock and barrel are matching. Bore is shiny, has strong rifling, and the action is smooth. There are no import marks anywhere on the metal and the cleaning rod is present. The words "MADE IN ITALY" are on the other side of the buttstock from the cartouche. These were stamped this way in the 50's and 60's on arrival in the US when Italy had them surplussed in favor of the M1 Garand. Canvas sling and 3 boxes of 6.5 Carcano ammunition are all included at this price. A true piece of history that has represented Italy in my WWII collection. I've decided to focus on other eras so Im looking to make a little room. Feel free to contact me with any questions or for any further images. Thanks for looking!

title: For Sale:  1943 Russian Mosin Nagant M38 Carbine w/Sling + 50 Rds 7.62x54R
postcontent: Selling my great condition 1943 Russian M38 Mosin Nagant, never fired by me, and as far as I can tell, never fired period. It's in as-new shape (at least, for Soviet wartime production) with all numbers matching. The only cosmetic issues are some slight nicks and scratches from being handled over the last 75 years; overall, it's in beautiful shape, especially considering its purpose and history. This model was manufactured at the Izhevsk Arsenal with the shorter, 20-1/4" barrel, without bayonet. This one was apparently arsenal refurbished after the war, as it has the counterbored muzzle which all of the refurbished rifles do. This particular model was only issued to second-line troops like combat engineers and such, and from its condition, probably saw no action. The fact that it was counterbored by the arsenal after the war means little, they did that to the vast majority of their rifles whether it was necessary or not. The bore of this gun is practically perfect, clean with well-defined rifling and no pitting or rust. If it was ever fired - particularly with the corrosive-primed Soviet military ammo - someone took great care to clean and preserve it. It's in exceptional shape.These M38's are the model you want if you're looking to make a sporter out of a Mosin and prefer the shorter barrel. The more common M91/30's have much longer barrels, and the M44 carbines all have a permanently affixed bayonet lug that has to be cut off or otherwise removed to fit a sporter-type stock. The nice thing about the M38 is, you can make most of the modifications necessary to turn it into a sporter while still preserving the ability to restore it to its original configuration.This rifle comes with the attached sling and cleaning rod, as well as 50 rounds of 7.62x54R ammunition. The ammo is the corrosive-primed Soviet standard issue, straight out of one of those metal "tuna can" ammo packs. The box you see in the photo originally belonged to a computer battery (I think), but it fits the ammo well and allows for safe storage (there's more ammo beneath the layer visible in the photo).I could only upload one photo for this listing, but I have many more high-resolution photos that I'd be happy to share upon request. This is an excellent example of a Mosin Nagant carbine, and if your'e looking for one of these you'll be very happy with it.This sale will be cash only. Local pickup only - no shipping.

postcontent: Used Steyr L9-A1. 4.5" barrel, 9mm. Bought new in early 2014. This is one of the early L9-A1's that came into the US. title: For Sale:  original percussion barrel
postcontent: The original buttplate is present and is convex-surfaced with a straight rear profile that measures 4 1/8” by 1 7/8”. The tang is 2 1/8” long and is round ended. Both the tang and buttplate screws have unmarred single-slot screws and the buttplate has a pewter patina. Deringer Rifle is in .58 caliber and it has a bright finish. The length of the rifle is 51 ¼” and the Barrel is 36” in length and is round and gradually tapers to the muzzle, which has a flat crown. The bore is rifled with seven .085” wide by .03” deep grooves. These barrels make one right hand turn in 48”. The bore is in excellent condition given the age of this rifle. The barrel has a deeply struck “P” proof stamp on the left, rear, which indicates this was an original percussion barrel..58 caliber versions being the more common of the two. Deringer Rifle examples are also known with both brown and bright metal finishes. All rifles manufactured by Deringer are believed to have been produced in 1861 and only 100 to 200 are believed to have been manufactured,I Accepted Postal Money Order or Bank Treansfer.Making this one of the rarest of Civil War rifles.The Rifle has its original Ramrod that measures 35 7/8” in length. The front end has a 7/8” long brass, slightly cupped trumpet head. The rear of the ramrod is threaded for a ball screw and wiper. The brass shows an old patina and the balance of the ramrod has a pewter patina. The Stock is a beautiful oil finished black walnut stock that is 48 ¼” in length. The stock has never been sanded and only has a few minor dings and scratches with no cracks noted. There is a small 1” x ¼” gouge in the bottom of the butt just to the rear of the trigger plate but it appears to be a very old, period ding.
